White aggressively defends b2.
I'm usually more aggressive (as in QxQ), but I'm trying to learn patience and development.

Red flag!  A move this aggressive from a worthy opponent screams "Reality Check!"  Hmm... I failed to notice that while my Queen was protected my Bishop on d6, she is also protecting my weak Pawn on b7...  If I capture his Bishop with my Queen, he could snag b7 and threaten my Rook...

But if he does, Bc6 would force White's Queen back to b3, where c4 would give me a fork that should win me his Bishop!  I should think my esteemed opponent sees this, and will play Ne5, or the more volatile Bb5...
Or maybe he'll attack my Queen...
He can now capture my b7 pawn for free, but I'd rather the imbalance than a White pawn on c5.
Surprised me again...
CMA
White blocks my Bishop.  Maybe I should castle now and develop my Knight later?
On second thought, I'd rather protect e5 from White's Knight...

White's position looks slightly more defensive than mine as I'm more advanced in the center, but he has a lot of fire power on that front.  I'm thinking e5 would press my center control, but I probably should castle...
But what the hell, e6 is a viable fork...
Was a viable fork...  I really should castle, but White has nothing to do next move but attack, and I don't like the lines I've analyzed, so...
I'll press White's Queen instead, and hope I can castle next move...
If I start a trade fest, we'll each end up with a Knight and two Rooks to support the pawn races, but my King's Black arse would still be in the open during the exchange....
So I'll tuck him into bed, and toss the ball to White...
Oops!  didn't mean to toss him that Pawn...  Maybe I can even the score...
Had to attack to defend, as Black had two pieces focused on d7 to my one...
OK.  I can pop his pawn with my Queen.
